WEBVTT

00:12.610 --> 00:16.575
When it was time for Elizabeth to have her baby, she gave birth to a son.

00:17.717 --> 00:23.364
Her neighbors and relatives heard that the Lord had shown her great mercy, and they shared her joy.

00:24.425 --> 00:31.034
On the eighth day, they came to circumcise the child, and they were going to name him after his father, Zachariah.

00:31.314 --> 00:34.719
But his mother spoke up and said, no, he used to be called John.

00:35.960 --> 00:40.306
They said to her, there is no one among your relatives who has that name.

00:41.538 --> 00:45.464
Then they made signs to his father to find out what he would like to name the child.

00:46.285 --> 00:49.028
He asked for a riding tablet and to everyone's astonishment.

00:49.069 --> 00:50.811
He wrote his name is John.

00:51.933 --> 00:56.980
Immediately his mouth was opened and his tongue set free and he began to speak praising God.

00:58.021 --> 01:01.546
All the neighbors were filled with all and throughout the hill country of Judea.

01:01.626 --> 01:03.729
People were talking about all these things.

01:05.151 --> 01:10.098
Everyone who heard this wondered about it asking, what then is this child going to be?

01:10.978 --> 01:12.340
for the Lord's hand was on him.

01:13.222 --> 01:14.203
This is the word of the Lord.

01:15.145 --> 01:16.026
Thanks be to God.

01:21.835 --> 01:31.230
Just about a week ago now, I attended parent teacher conferences for Hank and Simon, which at this point in my parenting life, I'm pretty used to.

01:31.270 --> 01:34.956
There's no mystery or anxiety associated with these meetings for me.

01:35.056 --> 01:39.122
I could tell you what the teacher's gonna say before I even walk into the classroom.

01:39.298 --> 01:42.984
Well, he's doing great, generally tracking academically.

01:43.024 --> 01:47.190
He is a bit of a talker, though, isn't he?

01:47.691 --> 01:59.349
Such a social butterfly, which reading between the lines means your son is tracking academically but will never, ever be quiet and still.

02:00.150 --> 02:06.559
So I'm sitting in that classroom in this little desk chair made for a seven-year-old, which feeling like Buddy the Elf, you know?

02:06.620 --> 02:08.242
Side note.

02:09.602 --> 02:17.172
Those of you in public education, how hard would it be to get another adult-sized chair in the room for these conferences that we do several times a year?

02:17.233 --> 02:26.345
It feels like a power play that I'm with a teacher in a rolling desk chair, and unlike my abdomen, it's pressed against laminated wood.

02:27.447 --> 02:36.619
Anyway, as I'm sitting there in that little chair in Hank's fourth grade classroom, I was transported in my imagination back to my own fourth grade classroom.

02:37.460 --> 02:38.642
I had Mrs. Smith.

02:39.266 --> 02:42.810
She's the star chart to track good and bad behavior.

02:42.850 --> 02:50.498
I ended up in the negatives week after week, which meant I spent a huge amount of time and time out.

02:51.699 --> 03:05.714
The universal punishment, which is utilized across cultures and eras celebrated by parents of every persuasion of lenient and strict, the undisputed champion of all consequences is time out.

03:06.722 --> 03:16.854
That's how most of us experience silence and solitude first as an unwanted disciplinary tactic to curb our bad behavior.

03:16.894 --> 03:24.243
There's something universal in us that fears quiet and alone, experiencing those conditions as torment.

03:26.565 --> 03:28.408
And for the most part, we never grow out of that.

03:29.008 --> 03:33.874
You know, the harshest punishment in the US prison system is solitary confinement.

03:34.530 --> 03:39.896
be quiet and alone for an extended period of time a long time out.

03:39.956 --> 03:43.501
That's as bad as it gets, even in adulthood.

03:44.101 --> 03:52.811
Quiet and alone is a combination of conditions that we only meet accidentally, at least at first.

03:52.831 --> 03:53.532
Hang on to that.

03:54.614 --> 03:57.737
Alongside the global church, we're currently living in the season of Advent.

03:57.797 --> 04:01.842
Our theme this year is First Light, which refers to that very first

04:02.274 --> 04:07.823
faint illumination in the night's darkness that welcomes each new day.

04:08.605 --> 04:22.608
First slide, that's a good way for us to understand a few of Jesus' most distant relatives, a family before Mary and Joseph, who make away for the dawning of the light of the world himself, Zechariah, Elizabeth, and John.

04:23.169 --> 04:27.276
So we'll meet those characters and the cadence Luke introduces them to us.

04:27.477 --> 04:28.338
Up first,

04:28.450 --> 04:29.311
is Zechariah.

04:29.351 --> 04:31.114
So look back from the earbibles.

04:31.154 --> 04:34.881
We're going to trace back from where we read a moment ago up to the top of the chapter.

04:34.941 --> 04:37.064
I want to begin reading from verse 5.

04:39.388 --> 04:47.802
In the time of King Herod, sorry, in the time of Herod, King of Judea, there was a priest named Zechariah who belonged to the priestly tribe of Abishah.

04:48.303 --> 04:51.568
His wife Elizabeth was also a descendant of Aaron.

04:51.688 --> 04:52.850
So hang on a second.

04:52.994 --> 05:06.554
When Luke sets out to tell the story of stories, the most far-reaching and important news that will ever be announced, he does not begin with angels Mary or Joseph, with shepherds Magi or Jesus.

05:06.654 --> 05:15.127
He opens with a few characters who won't be in any nativity scene, a priest named Zechariah and his wife Elizabeth.

05:15.968 --> 05:22.418
Zechariah were told as a descendant of Levi and has become a priest himself, verse seven.

05:22.978 --> 05:28.985
Both of them were righteous in the sight of God, observing all the Lord's commands and decrees blamelessly.

05:29.646 --> 05:35.953
Now that's a cue from Luke that would be obvious to his ancient readers, but is probably lost on most of us.

05:36.053 --> 05:46.925
The Jewish priesthood was pretty thoroughly corrupt in the first century, splintering into sex strongly divided against each other in response to their cultural moment.

05:47.366 --> 05:50.930
Some of the priests who were known as the Sadducees were famous

05:51.010 --> 05:56.937
for compromising the way of God to play ball with secular culture, politics, and economics.

05:57.158 --> 06:01.743
Luke is distinguishing Zechariah from that tribe of priests.

06:02.084 --> 06:09.533
He's a priest, yes, but believe it or not, he's a good, honorable, loving, and devout priest.

06:09.593 --> 06:16.722
It would be like me saying, he's an American politician, yes, but, keep reading.

06:18.146 --> 06:24.195
But they were childless because Elizabeth was not able to conceive, and they were both very old.

06:24.836 --> 06:29.823
So Zechariah and Elizabeth were righteous, blameless, and barren.

06:31.145 --> 06:32.827
One of these things is not like the other.

06:34.249 --> 06:45.746
First century Jewish spirituality held that physical illness often had a spiritual cause, particularly chronic illness or disability, something like barrenness or infertility.

06:45.858 --> 06:50.245
was viewed as a divine judgment for some type of egregious wrong.

06:50.686 --> 07:01.825
That's why a number of different places in the biblical story, including later in Luke chapter one, infertility is described as a source of personal shame and public disgrace.

07:02.265 --> 07:03.067
So check this out.

07:03.147 --> 07:08.476
Luke is setting up a puzzle right at the beginning of his gospel for you and I to ponder.

07:09.177 --> 07:12.242
If Zechariah and Elizabeth are righteous and blameless,

07:14.338 --> 07:16.621
Why is God withholding blessing from them?

07:19.405 --> 07:35.306
One of the best friends I've ever had in my life, and one of those women who seem tailor-made to be a mom, spent her early adult life mothering all of her friends in a really good way, planned to have four kids minimum.

07:35.326 --> 07:41.234
When she and her husband decided that they were ready, they just couldn't get pregnant, went from

07:41.474 --> 07:51.907
doctor to doctor to doctor with no diagnosis, round after round of IVF with no progress, prayed and prayed and the years just passed and passed.

07:53.529 --> 08:00.818
What kind of God designs a woman's body with the capacity to carry life, then withholds life?

08:02.680 --> 08:10.610
What kind of God would grant child after child to thousands of oops stories and then ignores the

08:10.754 --> 08:14.379
Ease, prayers of one of his daughters.

08:15.681 --> 08:17.183
Have you ever asked questions like those?

08:19.185 --> 08:19.966
That's the puzzle.

08:20.988 --> 08:23.872
That's the puzzle Luke is inviting you and I to ponder.

08:24.453 --> 08:24.913
Read on.

08:25.854 --> 08:37.330
Once when Zachariah's division was on duty and he was serving as priest before God, he was chosen by lot according to the custom of the priesthood to go into the temple of the Lord and burn incense.

08:38.146 --> 08:41.169
So the Jewish priesthood was a really well-run organization.

08:41.350 --> 08:47.416
At the time of Jesus' birth, there were an estimated 20,000-plus active priests in service.

08:47.797 --> 08:53.343
They were grouped into 24 divisions rotating weekly to serve the temple.

08:53.763 --> 08:58.509
Each division served temple duty twice a year for week-long shifts.

08:59.369 --> 09:03.474
The priests would then sleep at the temple when they were on duty, a lot like

09:03.554 --> 09:07.700
Firefighters sleep at the firehouse when they're on duty in modern culture.

09:08.161 --> 09:22.722
Luke is telling us here that when the time came for the sect of Abi Jia to serve, Zechariah drew the straw with the prestigious role of burning incense in the room before the Holy of Holies.

09:23.202 --> 09:23.944
So check this out.

09:23.984 --> 09:31.154
This is a simplified blueprint of what should be in your imagination when you think about the Jewish temple.

09:31.618 --> 09:37.205
The holy of holies is the innermost room where God lived and not metaphorically either.

09:37.585 --> 09:44.573
There's an entire Old Testament to explain the way that God took up residence among his people in his temple.

09:45.094 --> 09:54.365
Zechariah had probably waited his entire life to get this close to God and serve God's people, this profoundly.

09:54.725 --> 09:58.770
For seven days, he had drawn the straw

09:59.074 --> 10:06.765
to crash in a cot next to the Creator and offer up the most sacred of prayers for all of God's people.

10:07.266 --> 10:11.191
This was undoubtedly an honor professionally.

10:12.894 --> 10:17.300
And equally, it had to be painful personally.

10:19.783 --> 10:24.530
The tragic irony is, Zechariah's own prayers haven't been answered.

10:25.314 --> 10:30.903
And now he is the one selected to offer prayers on behalf of a nation's worth of people.

10:32.165 --> 10:43.703
He's nearing retirement age, and he's finally selected for the most honorable of all priestly roles, but to come near to God is also to face how deeply this God has disappointed me.

10:44.885 --> 10:50.674
So Zachariah is invited to bring his grief, disappointment, and angst about divine justice.

10:50.818 --> 10:52.903
right into the presence of God.

10:53.324 --> 11:00.721
And bringing my pain into God's presence involves the intensification of that pain for the risk of the healing of it.

11:02.064 --> 11:03.026
Back to the story.

11:03.906 --> 11:07.811
than an angel of the Lord appeared to him, standing at the right side of the altar of incense.

11:08.252 --> 11:15.562
When Zechariah saw him, he was startled and gripped with fear, but the angel said to him, do not be afraid, Zechariah, your prayer has been heard.

11:15.582 --> 11:19.307
Your wife Elizabeth will bear you a son, and you are to call him John.

11:19.367 --> 11:20.669
Scan down to verse 18.

11:21.470 --> 11:24.334
Zechariah asked the angel, how can I be sure of this?

11:25.075 --> 11:27.559
I'm an old man, and my wife is well along in years.

11:28.540 --> 11:32.946
So Zechariah is asking for confirmation, which is understandable.

11:33.538 --> 11:42.352
I mean, who hasn't had a profound spiritual experience and then later wondered if it was really God I was hearing or if I was just hearing what I wanted to hear.

11:43.293 --> 11:47.259
So look, on one hand, this request for confirmation is entirely reasonable.

11:48.181 --> 11:56.213
At the same time though, Zechariah is asking for confirmation from an angel.

11:58.256 --> 11:59.678
I love the angel's response.

11:59.738 --> 12:02.162
Verse 19, the angel said to him,

12:02.658 --> 12:03.999
I am Gabriel.

12:05.160 --> 12:09.925
I stand in the presence of God and have been sent to speak to you to tell you this good news.

12:10.005 --> 12:17.272
It's kind of like, uh, Zach, I'm gleaming white and levitating nine inches off the ground.

12:17.372 --> 12:19.895
How much more clear could God be making this for you?

12:22.077 --> 12:28.223
There's so much humanity in this story because we've all been Zechariah.

12:30.265 --> 12:31.826
Some of us are today.

12:33.314 --> 12:42.044
We identify with our disappointment at such a depth that it becomes the lens through which we see and experience everything else, even God.

12:43.846 --> 12:45.868
God is faithful to the whole world.

12:45.908 --> 12:46.909
Absolutely.

12:46.929 --> 12:50.573
He will redeem all things, gather all nations, right all wrong.

12:51.214 --> 12:55.078
I believe that, but don't ask me to believe that God will heal my body.

12:56.459 --> 12:58.962
That God will restore my shattered marriage.

12:59.170 --> 13:01.954
The God will satisfy my longing for a companion.

13:02.295 --> 13:05.239
The God will bring back my long gone son or daughter.

13:05.600 --> 13:06.762
That is too personal.

13:08.064 --> 13:13.112
Don't ask me to believe that after all this waiting, God's going to grant Elizabeth and I a baby.

13:13.352 --> 13:16.357
I'm here to do a job to pray for the people outside.

13:16.437 --> 13:17.759
Don't make this that personal.

13:17.799 --> 13:20.964
I can't take that.

13:20.984 --> 13:22.386
The depth at which some of us

13:22.594 --> 13:33.086
identify with our own disappointment, causes us to define all that we see and experience through a set of well-calculated, lowered expectations for God and the way he deals with us.

13:34.367 --> 13:43.818
Verse 20, and now you will be silent and not able to speak until the day this happens because you did not believe my words, which will come true at their appointed time.

13:46.001 --> 13:48.343
Quiet and alone are consequences, right?

13:50.165 --> 13:50.866
A punishment.

13:52.674 --> 13:59.642
That's how we experience them first when they're enforced upon us by an outside authority like this.

13:59.743 --> 14:02.045
It's a punishment.

14:02.105 --> 14:04.488
And that's an experience we never grow out of.

14:04.528 --> 14:11.757
You'll be quiet and alone in some very real sense until this promise named John is alive in flesh and blood and held in your own arms.

14:13.239 --> 14:14.320
So here's my question.

14:16.242 --> 14:19.186
Is God putting Zechariah in a time out?

14:22.178 --> 14:23.801
Is silence a gift?

14:25.764 --> 14:26.726
Or is it a punishment?

14:31.254 --> 14:34.339
Advent is not Christmas.

14:34.359 --> 14:38.386
It's a time of slowing, quieting, and stealing ourselves for the sake of Christmas.

14:39.618 --> 14:44.903
Since the inception of the early church, Advent has been observed as a time to grieve.

14:44.943 --> 14:58.236
Nature's darkest days of the year repurposed as a time to look into the darkest corners of my own life, a time to retreat intentionally into the quiet face, my disappointment, my pain, my angst, my anger, and my grief.

14:58.776 --> 15:04.182
Today, Advent Quiet has been replaced by Christmas noise.

15:05.583 --> 15:08.786
Advent's solitude exchanged for Christmas busyness.

15:09.730 --> 15:17.497
We take the very time of the year reserved for quietly grieving, and we replace it with busyness, talking, entertainment, and endless celebration.

15:17.537 --> 15:24.804
Maybe we're just that happy with that much more to celebrate than our ancient spiritual ancestors had.

15:25.365 --> 15:26.366
I doubt that, though.

15:27.967 --> 15:31.891
More likely we're disappointed, grief-stricken, and we don't know how to face it.

15:33.172 --> 15:34.413
So we busy ourselves.

15:34.553 --> 15:39.378
We push away our pain and chatter treats, cocktails, and sentiments.

15:40.930 --> 16:01.928
One of the most fascinating books I read in the last year was called Wintering by Katherine May, and it was an exploration about how modern Western human beings are the first species in all of recorded history, not to utilize the summer for some type of preparation for the inevitable arrival of the winter.

16:03.570 --> 16:05.554
Every animal species we know of

16:05.826 --> 16:15.421
does some sort of preparation for the impending winter every summer, some sort of storing away to survive when everything around them is dark, cold, and dead.

16:16.542 --> 16:21.951
And actually every tribe or people group or culture that you trace throughout history has done the same.

16:22.251 --> 16:25.055
They've used summer to prepare for the winter.

16:25.436 --> 16:32.146
Modern people though, I mean, we live in a world of grocery stores and fluorescent lights and central heating and Amazon Prime and DoorDash.

16:33.282 --> 16:36.548
So we don't need to prepare in the summer to survive the winter.

16:36.869 --> 16:39.134
And I'm very grateful for that true story.

16:39.454 --> 16:45.145
Just a couple of weeks ago, I wanted Poke, Kirsten wanted Vietnamese, we couldn't decide which one.

16:45.166 --> 16:46.829
So we both ordered DoorDash.

16:48.512 --> 16:53.522
And the drivers arrived in my driveway at the same moment.

16:54.498 --> 16:57.441
And they both walked up to the door looking really confused.

16:57.561 --> 17:00.685
And then when we both came to the door, they just got judgy.

17:00.745 --> 17:02.667
I could see it in their eyes immediately.

17:02.687 --> 17:03.828
But I was delighted.

17:03.888 --> 17:08.553
I'm very grateful to live at the moment in history that I'm living in.

17:08.994 --> 17:14.239
But Catherine May's observation carries profound implications for our inner lives as well.

17:15.781 --> 17:20.306
And counsel throughout church history has been that consolation

17:21.154 --> 17:32.031
Our spiritual summers, when God seems close and available and clear, consolation is properly stewarded when we store up the treasures of those seasons.

17:32.872 --> 17:42.968
Remember and savor the promises, the blessings, because we know that we're going to need them in the inevitable arrival of desolation.

17:44.310 --> 17:49.778
Those spiritual winters, when God seems far and absent and confusing.

17:50.402 --> 17:57.132
If we do not prepare for winter, then we do not deal with barrenness very well.

18:00.137 --> 18:11.695
With interruption, intrusion, and pain, with disappointment, disillusion, and disorder, with loss, betrayal, loneliness, and the God who didn't stop any of it and refuses to exploit himself.

18:14.319 --> 18:16.242
Advent is preparation for winter.

18:17.090 --> 18:20.994
It is facing and grieving our disappointments so that they don't define us.

18:22.696 --> 18:32.427
The church invites our people to zig while the culture is zagging, to grow quiet amid all the noise to choose solitude and stillness in a season of busyness and chatter.

18:34.369 --> 18:42.898
The World Health Organization named noise pollution as the second worst environmental toxin after air pollution, worse than oil or gas.

18:43.554 --> 18:51.962
A recent study in the European Union found that noise pollution was responsible for a million daylies a year in Europe alone.

18:52.022 --> 19:04.454
That's disabled disability adjusted life years, meaning you live to 70 when you should have lived to 73 because you happen to be on a noisy block or your apartments above a busy cafe.

19:05.535 --> 19:13.362
One study found that prescriptions for anxiety medication rise 28% for every 10 decibel increase in neighborhood noise.

19:14.242 --> 19:26.879
In an article first published in a scientific journal titled, This Is Your Brain on Silence, the journalist David Gross says, the body reacts immediately and powerfully to loud noise, even in the middle of deep sleep.

19:27.660 --> 19:38.796
Neurophysiological research suggests that noise is first activate the amygdala, clusters of neurons located in the temporal lobes of the brain, associated with memory formation and emotion.

19:38.836 --> 19:43.442
The activation prompts an immediate release of stress hormones like cortisol.

19:43.522 --> 19:50.693
People who live in consistently loud environments often experience chronically elevated levels of stress hormones.

19:52.095 --> 19:57.483
The psychological development of human beings was formed in a much, much quieter world.

19:58.345 --> 20:06.037
Every time I go camping or backpacking, the first thing I notice is that it's so quiet out here.

20:08.220 --> 20:09.522
And that was just normal.

20:10.562 --> 20:13.474
for the vast majority of the world for most of human history.

20:15.000 --> 20:18.674
In nature, pretty much everything that's loud is a threat.

20:19.554 --> 20:22.999
a bear or a cougar, a thundercloud or an earthquake.

20:23.419 --> 20:41.985
So when you're living in Portland, you might think, oh, that's just the hum of the HVAC or the beep of another delivery truck or the rumble of the max, but your body is still interpreting noise over a certain decibel level as a threat, activating and releasing stress hormones into your central nervous system all the time.

20:43.728 --> 20:48.114
Our cities are so noisy, but so is our culture.

20:48.930 --> 21:04.146
Right, we could talk about the noise of Portland, or the noise of Christmas, or we could just talk about the noise of the front page of the New York Times, the latest episode of the Huberman podcast, and the incessant political war that we're all living through.

21:05.090 --> 21:17.848
Right, there's external noise, but you're also dealing with all the internal noise of the global, national, local news headlines, the noise of political and ideological banter that's on your screen and around your table and in your own head.

21:18.428 --> 21:31.346
And the next health thing you're worried about when you thought you were just counting macros and counting steps, but now you've learned you've been ingesting microplastics this whole time and you need to drink electrolyte powder every day too.

21:33.026 --> 21:35.450
Noise pollution is all around us.

21:36.972 --> 21:48.890
But has there ever been a time and place in world history with more noise pollution than 21st century America in December?

21:52.956 --> 21:59.986
Advent is a four-week window set aside in the year to intentionally follow and secularize footsteps to draw.

22:00.098 --> 22:06.084
nearer to God's presence, bringing our grief, our pain, our disappointments into God's presence.

22:06.584 --> 22:14.011
Has the church ever needed Advent's invitation to silence and solitude more than right now?

22:16.293 --> 22:29.586
I wonder if the greatest threat to your and my spiritual formation as we swim in a world of this much noise pollution isn't so much hedonism as it is just distraction.

22:31.938 --> 22:37.748
Because the truth is, we will not grow much spiritually if we are busy.

22:39.311 --> 22:41.936
We won't grow much spiritually if we're in a hurry.

22:41.956 --> 22:53.136
We will find it very hard to hear God's voice if our minds are noisy and cluttered, and we will not receive the gifts God longs to give us if we're constantly distracted.

22:54.719 --> 22:56.402
My friend AJ Sherrill writes,

22:56.674 --> 23:07.609
The primary task of a Christian in Advent is growing one's capacity to perceive the story by slowing down long enough to receive it.

23:07.629 --> 23:13.116
Too much talking, doubting, spending, and stressing crowds out Emmanuel.

23:14.098 --> 23:14.859
God with us.

23:17.983 --> 23:22.549
But there's nothing wrong with Christmas parties and fun plans during the holiday season.

23:23.450 --> 23:26.194
Busyness is not inherently evil.

23:27.266 --> 23:31.493
There's nothing wrong with Christmas music and catching up with friends and get togethers.

23:33.015 --> 23:41.408
But the truth is, busyness and noise are also some of our best subconscious strategies for avoiding the reality of our lives.

23:42.951 --> 23:47.538
When we grow disappointed with life, we often just stay busy in order to numb our pain.

23:48.386 --> 23:49.387
We slow down.

23:49.448 --> 23:58.281
We're left with the chaos of our inner lives that we effortlessly hold at bay, so long as we never stop moving and scheming and planning and doing.

23:58.621 --> 24:04.770
But if you want to see the sunrise, then you first have to look long and hard into the dark.

24:06.633 --> 24:08.256
And that brings us to Elizabeth.

24:08.736 --> 24:12.562
Let's pick back up with Luke in verse 24 of chapter 1.

24:13.922 --> 24:20.570
After this, his wife Elizabeth became pregnant and for five months remained in seclusion.

24:20.630 --> 24:22.992
The Lord has done this for me.

24:23.032 --> 24:27.798
She said, in these days he has shown his favor and taken away my disgrace among the people.

24:28.739 --> 24:38.450
Now this English word, seclusion in Luke's original Greek is paracribo, which interestingly is also the biblical word for solitude.

24:39.266 --> 24:49.319
Elizabeth, hearing God whisper the same promise into her deep place of pain and grief, does not question God like her husband, Zachariah.

24:49.679 --> 24:57.869
She quiets herself, retreats into solitude, and attempts to listen more attentively to God.

24:57.889 --> 25:01.374
A couple weeks ago, I was at a friend's cabin for the weekend.

25:01.934 --> 25:07.922
And on Saturday morning, I made a cup of coffee and I went and I sat on the deck and I began to pray,

25:08.418 --> 25:09.339
Holy Spirit.

25:10.721 --> 25:17.970
And then I heard this, and it startled me.

25:18.010 --> 25:23.817
And I looked up and ducked because I heard something above my head, and it was just a bird flying about 30 feet over me.

25:24.679 --> 25:28.624
Not a particularly large bird, just a bird.

25:29.965 --> 25:32.028
